5–1348","1301–1361":"1301–1361","1316–1374":"1316–1374","1317–1370":"1317–1370","1240–1290":"1240–1290","1257–1326":"1257–1326","11 November 1276":"11 November 1276","1374":"1374","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1361":"1361","1282":"1282","1370":"1370","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1326":"1326","1348":"1348","1312":"1312","1257":"1257","1301":"1301","1321":"1321","1277":"1277","18 December 1290":"18 December 1290","1319":"1319","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","Sweden":"Sweden","Oslo, Norway":"Oslo, Norway","Stockholm, Sverige":"Stockholm, Sweden","Visingsö, Jönköping, Sweden":"Visingsö, Jönköping, Sweden","Kalmar, Uppsala, Sweden":"Kalmar, Uppsala, Sweden","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Magnusson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Niels, Anders, Erland, Gisli, Kerstin, Lars, Nils, Ottar, Thor.  German Hans, Kurt, Fritz.","Swedish: patronymic from the personal name   Magnus  .","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, or North German   Magnussen  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Magnus","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Bernd, Egon, Erwin, Kurt, Otto, Reinhard, Volker, Wilhelm, Wolfgang.","German, Flemish, and Walloon: from the personal name <i>Magnus</i>, which is from the Latin adjective <i>magnus</i> ‘great’ or a Latinized form of a short form of ancient Germanic compound names based on the element <i>magan</i> ‘strength, might’. The name was borne by several early Christian saints, including St. Magnus (8th century), a monk in St. Gallen in Switzerland and missionary in Allgäu in southern Germany, whose real name was <i>Magnoald</i>. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine). In Belgium, it may also be a Latinized (humanistic) form of Walloon   Legrand  .","English, Scottish, Swedish, Danish, Norwegian, and North German: from the Scandinavian personal name <i>Magnus</i>, borne by Magnus the Good (died 1047), king of Norway and Denmark, who was named for the Emperor Charlemagne, Latin <i>Carolus Magnus</i> ‘Charles the Great’, under the impression that <i>Magnus</i> was a personal name. The name spread from Norway to the eastern Scandinavian royal houses, and became popular all over Scandinavia and thence in the English Danelaw. It has also been adopted as a Jewish name."]},{"name":"Magnuson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Nels, Helmer, Sven, Kerstin, Alf, Anders, Hilma, Knut, Monrad, Thor.","Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish   Magnusson  .","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Magnussen  , a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Manson","meanings":["Scottish (mainly the Northern Isles): shortened form of   Magnusson  .","English: patronymic, probably sometimes from the Middle English personal name <i>Man</i>, <i>Manne</i> (Old English <i>Mann(a)</i> or Old Danish <i>Manni</i>) + <i>-son</i>; compare   Mann  . Occasionally perhaps from a Middle English personal name <i>Mainstan</i> (Old English <i>Mægenstān</i>, from <i>mægen</i> ‘might, power’ + <i>stān</i> ‘stone’).","Americanized form of Swedish <b>Månsson</b> (rarely <b>Månson</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Måns</i>, a derivative of   Magnus  . Compare   Monson  ."]}]},{"name":"Erik","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Later variant of   Eirik  , now in frequent use, especially in Sweden."],"variants":[{"name":"Eric","meanings":["Of Old Norse origin, from <i>ei</i> ‘ever, always’ (or <i>einn</i> ‘one, alone’) + <i>ríkr</i> ‘ruler’ (  see  Eirik   ). It was introduced into Britain by Scandinavian settlers before the Norman Conquest. As a modern given name, it was revived in the mid 19th century and has remained in use since."]},{"name":"Eirik","meanings":["From the Old Norse personal name <i>Eirikr</i>, a compound of <i>ei</i> ‘ever, always’ (or <i>einn</i> ‘one, alone’) + <i>ríkr</i> ‘ruler’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1702075,"age":24,"year":"1306","julianDay":2198067,"title":"The Hatuna Games","description":"A conflict on September 29, 1306, between Birger, King of Sweden, and his brothers, the dukes Eric Magnusson and Valdemar Magnusson is known as The Hatuna Games. The brothers arrived to a party late in the night at King Birger's estate. The dukes captured and imprisoned Birger and his wife in Nykoping Castle's dungeon. Duke Eric then gained power over Sweden.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1357048,"age":36,"year":"1318","julianDay":2202450,"description":"Peasants revolted against King.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Erik Magnusson was born in 1282, in Sweden, his father, King Magnus Ladulås Birgersson King of Sweden, was 43 and his mother, Helvig av Holstein, was 26. He married Ingeborg Håkansdotter in 1312, in Oslo, Norway. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1318, in his hometown, at the age of 36."},"et":{"1282–1318":"1282–1318","1277–1319":"1277–1319","1280–1321":"1280–1321","1285–1318":"1285–1318","1285–1348":"1285–1348","1301–1361":"1301–1361","1316–1374":"1316–1374","1317–1370":"1317–1370","1240–1290":"1240–1290","1257–1326":"1257–1326","11 November 1276":"11. november 1276","1374":"1374","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1361":"1361","1282":"1282","1370":"1370","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1326":"1326","1348":"1348","1312":"1312","1257":"1257","1301":"1301","1321":"1321","1277":"1277","18 December 1290":"18. detsember 1290","1319":"1319","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","Sweden":"Rootsi","Oslo, Norway":"Oslo, Norra","Stockholm, Sverige":"Stockholm, Rootsi","Visingsö, Jönköping, Sweden":"Visingsö, Jönköping, Rootsi","Kalmar, Uppsala, Sweden":"Kalmar, Uppsala, Rootsi"},"fi":{"1282–1318":"1282–1318","1277–1319":"1277–1319","1280–1321":"1280–1321","1285–1318":"1285–1318","1285–1348":"1285–1348","1